71. Python data structures
A data structure is a way of organizing and storing data so that it can be accessed and modified efficiently.
Data structures are primarily classified into primitive data structures (basic types built into languages like integers and booleans) and non-primitive data structures (complex structures that organize multiple values).
Non-primitive structures are further divided into linear and non-linear

primitive datastructures:- 
These are the most fundamental building blocks directly operated on by machine instructions. They typically hold a single value
int float bool character

Linear Data Structures:-
In these structures, data elements are arranged in a sequential, single-dimension line where each item connects to its direct neighbor before and after.
Array:
An array is a linear data structure that stores a collection of elements in contiguous memory locations.
Contiguous Memory is defined as a type of memory allocation where data is stored in a sequential and uninterrupted manner in the system's memory

strict arrays in Python cannot store different data types; they are strictly homogeneous. 
However, Python offers other highly flexible data structures like lists, as well as third-party library workarounds, that allow you to manage mixed data types.
built in array module - homogenous 
built in list - hereogenues

string:
In Python, a string is officially classified as a built-in data type, but conceptually, it also functions as a linear data structure.
From a syntax and language perspective, a string is a core data type represented by the str class.
From a computer science perspective, a string is a linear data structure because it organizes and stores data in a specific arrangement.

linkedlist:
A linked list is a linear data structure where elements are not stored in contiguous memory locations, but are instead chained together using references or pointers
Singly Linked List: Each node links exclusively forward to the next node; the final node points to None.
Doubly Linked List: Nodes store both next and prev pointers, facilitating bidirectional traversal at the expense of additional memory.
Circular Linked List: The last node's pointer circles back to the head node, removing any terminal None point.


What is a Stack?
A stack is a linear data structure that operates on the Last In, First Out (LIFO) principle. The last item added to the stack is always the very first one to be removed.
Real-World Analogy: Think of a pile of dinner plates. You can only place a new plate on the top, and you can only remove a plate from the top.
Core Operations:
push(): Adds an item to the top of the stack.
pop(): Removes and returns the top item from the stack.
peek() or top(): Views the top item without removing it.
isEmpty(): Checks if the stack is completely empty.
Common Use Cases:
Reverting states using Undo/Redo functionality in text editors.
Tracking web pages in Browser History (the back button).
Managing active functions via the compiler Call Stack during recursion.

What is a Queue?
A queue is a linear data structure that operates on the First In, First Out (FIFO) principle. The item that enters the data structure first is processed and removed first. 
It uses two separate ends: the Rear (for adding data) and the Front (for removing data).
Real-World Analogy: Think of a line of people waiting to buy tickets at a counter. The first person to join the line is served first.
Core Operations:
enqueue(): Adds an item to the end (rear) of the queue.
dequeue(): Removes and returns the item at the front of the queue.
getFront(): Views the first element without removing it.
isEmpty(): Checks if the queue has no elements left.
Common Use Cases:
Scheduling processes in operating systems (e.g., CPU Task Scheduling).
Handling shared resources sequentially (e.g., managing print jobs in a Printer Queue).
Graph traversal algorithms like Breadth-First Search (BFS)

None linear : Non-linear data structures organize data elements hierarchically or in interconnected networks rather than in a sequential line.

Trees
A Tree Data Structure represents a hierarchy of nodes connected by edges, beginning with a single root node. Each node contains a value and references to its "child" nodes.

Graphs
A Graph Data Structure consists of a finite set of vertices (or nodes) interconnected by edges. 
Graphs are ideal for mapping networks where connections don't follow a strict parent-child hierarchy, such as social networks or map routes

Heaps
A Heap is a specialized tree-based data structure that satisfies the "heap property"

